# Vendor relationships — [APP_NAME]

Third-party services and libraries this project relies on, why they were
chosen, what they replaced, and the cost (effort, contractual, technical) of
swapping them out.

This file is read by `rsct_get_knowledge(category="vendor-relationships")`
and by `rsct_persona_review` (Architect + DevOps personas). Spec phase
surfaces relevant vendors when proposing functionality they cover — so
Claude proposes "use SendGrid" instead of "set up SMTP server", because
SendGrid is already in the stack and paid for.

**Bias correction:** Without this file, Claude defaults to whatever has the
most documentation in its training set. With this file, Claude proposes
what the org already pays for and operates.

---

## When to capture an entry here

Capture or update when **any** of the following is true:

- A new third-party (SaaS, library, API, infrastructure provider) is
adopted in this project.
- A vendor is dropped (the drop reason goes here too; the abandoned
approach goes in `anti-decisions.md`).
- A vendor undergoes material change: acquisition, pricing model shift,
deprecation announcement, security incident affecting our usage.
- A vendor's lock-in surface grows (new feature adopted that increases
churn cost). Update the entry.
- During a session, someone asks "why are we using X?" and the answer
isn't already here. Capture the answer.

## When NOT to capture here

- Internal tools, services, or libraries built by the team — those are part
of the architecture, not vendors.
- Generic open-source dependencies pinned via package manager without
explicit decision (e.g., `lodash`) — capture only if there's a story
(security incident, performance issue, version pin reason).
- Personal services used by individuals (a dev's local IDE plugin) —
unrelated to project state.
- Pricing details that are sensitive — keep tier/scale-band, not exact
quotes. This file may end up in a public repo; do not leak commercial terms.

---

## Entry schema

Each entry follows this exact structure:

```
### VR-NNN — <vendor / service name>
- **Role in this project:** <specific, concrete — "transactional email for
  password reset and order confirmation", not just "email">
- **Adopted:** <YYYY-MM-DD> (replaces: <prior solution or "none">)
- **Chosen because:**
  - <reason 1 — with measurement or anchor>
  - <reason 2>
  - <reason 3>
- **Alternatives considered:**
  - <alt 1 — why discarded>
  - <alt 2 — why discarded>
- **Lock-in surface:** <which features/APIs/data formats we depend on. The
  more specific, the better the churn-cost estimate>
- **Churn cost (estimated):** <low | medium | high | very high — with a
  one-line reason; ideally person-weeks of swap effort>
- **Cost tier (sanitized):** <free / sub-$100/mo / sub-$1k/mo / sub-$10k/mo /
  higher — DO NOT write exact dollar amounts>
- **Account owner (internal):** <name or role; how to reach for renewal/escalation>
- **Vendor contact (if applicable):** <named CSM / support tier>
- **Risk watch:** <known concerns — pricing trajectory, acquisition rumors,
  competitor in our space, etc.>
- **Related:** <ADRs that govern this choice, BRs that constrain usage,
  AD entries describing prior abandoned vendors>
- **Captured:** <YYYY-MM-DD> by <dev|claude>
```

Numbering: VR-001+ sequential, append-only. Dropped vendors stay in the
file with `Status: dropped YYYY-MM-DD — reason: <>; replaced by VR-NNN`.

